# google-bigquery Best Practices

This document serves as a comprehensive guide to using Google BigQuery, emphasizing performance, maintainability, and best practices that should be adopted by every developer on the team.

## Code Organization and Structure

### Use Explicit Column Selection
Avoid using `SELECT *` to improve performance and reduce costs. Always specify the columns you need.

❌ BAD:
```sql
SELECT * FROM my_dataset.my_table;
```

✅ GOOD:
```sql
SELECT column1, column2, column3 FROM my_dataset.my_table;
```

### Maintain Consistent Indentation
Use consistent indentation to improve readability. The standard is 2 spaces per indentation level.

✅ GOOD:
```sql
SELECT 
  column1,
  column2
FROM 
  my_dataset.my_table
WHERE 
  column1 = 'value';
```

### Use UPPER CASE for SQL Keywords
For better readability and consistency, always write SQL keywords in uppercase.

✅ GOOD:
```sql
SELECT column1, column2 FROM my_dataset.my_table WHERE column1 = 'value';
```

### Use AS for Aliases
Always use the `AS` keyword when creating aliases for clarity.

✅ GOOD:
```sql
SELECT column1 AS c1, column2 AS c2 FROM my_dataset.my_table;
```

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Prefer Time-Partitioned Tables
Use time-partitioned tables instead of date-sharded tables for better performance and easier management.

✅ GOOD:
```sql
CREATE TABLE my_dataset.my_table
PARTITION BY DATE(timestamp_column) AS
SELECT * FROM source_table;
```

### Use Clustering for Frequent Query Columns
Cluster tables on columns that are frequently used in `WHERE`, `GROUP BY`, and `JOIN` clauses, ordered by cardinality.

✅ GOOD:
```sql
CREATE TABLE my_dataset.my_table
CLUSTER BY column1, column2 AS
SELECT * FROM source_table;
```

### Leverage Materialized Views
For repeated aggregations, use materialized views to avoid scanning the base table.

✅ GOOD:
```sql
CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW my_dataset.my_view AS
SELECT column1, COUNT(*) AS count
FROM my_dataset.my_table
GROUP BY column1;
```

## Performance Considerations

### Filter Early in JOINs
Filter and aggregate data as early as possible in your queries to reduce the amount of data shuffled across the network.

✅ GOOD:
```sql
SELECT a.column1, COUNT(b.column2)
FROM my_dataset.table_a AS a
JOIN my_dataset.table_b AS b ON a.id = b.a_id
WHERE a.status = 'active'
GROUP BY a.column1;
```

### Use APPROX_COUNT_DISTINCT
When counting unique values, prefer `APPROX_COUNT_DISTINCT` for better performance over `COUNT(DISTINCT ...)`.

✅ GOOD:
```sql
SELECT APPROX_COUNT_DISTINCT(column1) AS unique_count
FROM my_dataset.my_table;
```

### Monitor Costs and Performance
Utilize `INFORMATION_SCHEMA.JOBS` to monitor job performance and costs, identifying any skewed stages.

✅ GOOD:
```sql
SELECT *
FROM `region-us`.INFORMATION_SCHEMA.JOBS_BY_USER
WHERE user_email = 'your-email@example.com'
ORDER BY creation_time DESC;
```

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Avoid SELECT * in Subqueries
Using `SELECT *` in subqueries can lead to unexpected costs and performance issues. Always specify columns.

❌ BAD:
```sql
SELECT * FROM (
    SELECT * FROM my_dataset.my_table
) AS subquery;
```

✅ GOOD:
```sql
SELECT column1, column2 FROM (
    SELECT column1, column2 FROM my_dataset.my_table
) AS subquery;
```

### Be Cautious with JOINs
Joining large tables without filtering can lead to performance degradation. Always apply filters before joining.

❌ BAD:
```sql
SELECT a.column1, b.column2
FROM my_dataset.table_a AS a
JOIN my_dataset.table_b AS b ON a.id = b.a_id;
```

✅ GOOD:
```sql
SELECT a.column1, b.column2
FROM my_dataset.table_a AS a
JOIN my_dataset.table_b AS b ON a.id = b.a_id
WHERE a.status = 'active';
```

## Testing Approaches

### Use Query Validation
Always validate your queries using the BigQuery console before execution to catch syntax errors early.

✅ GOOD:
```sql
-- Run this in the BigQuery console to validate
SELECT column1, column2 FROM my_dataset.my_table WHERE column1 = 'value';
```

### Automate Formatting
Use the built-in BigQuery console tool to automate SQL formatting for consistency and readability.

## Conclusion
By adhering to these best practices, you can ensure your BigQuery usage is efficient, maintainable, and cost-effective. Always remember to review and refactor your queries regularly to align with these guidelines.